onously available. In Next.js 15, `params` became a `Promise` to better handle async data loading. This affects all async components and functions that receive `params`. Failing to await the `Promise` can result in the following error:\n\n```\nType error: Type '{ params: { slug: string; }; }' does not satisfy the constraint 'PageProps'. Types of property 'params' are incompatible. Type '{ slug: string; }' is missing the following properties from type 'Promise ': then, catch, finally, [Symbol.toStringTag]Static worker exited with code: 1 and signal: null\n```\n\nThis is part of Next.js 15â€™s improvements to server components and dynamic route handling.\n\n## Example: Breaking Change in Action\n\nHereâ€™s how the behavior differs between Next.js 14 and 15:\n\n**Old Way (Next.js 14):**\n\n```\nexport default async function Page({â€¦\n```\n\n[**Written by Matija Å½iberna**](https://medium.com/@matijazib?source=post_page---post_author_info--96075e04f7b6---------------------------------------)\n\n[119 followers](https://medium.com/@matijazib/followers?source=post_page---post",
