      "author": "Md. Shahadath Alam",
      "text": "Agree & Join LinkedIn\n\nBy clicking Continue to join or sign in, you agree to LinkedInâ€™s [User Agreement](https://www.linkedin.com/legal/user-agreement?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_user-agreement), [Privacy Policy](https://www.linkedin.com/legal/privacy-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_privacy-policy), and [Cookie Policy](https://www.linkedin.com/legal/cookie-policy?trk=linkedin-tc_auth-button_cookie-policy).\n\nLinkedIn\n\nLinkedIn is better on the app\n\nDonâ€™t have the app? Get it in the Microsoft Store.\n\n[Open the app](ms-windows-store://pdp/?ProductId=9WZDNCRFJ4Q7&mode=mini&cid=guest_desktop_upsell)\n\n [Skip to main content](https://www.linkedin.com/www.linkedin.com#main-content)\n\nAs Next.js evolves, certain behaviors and best practices around dynamic routing have changed. One of the latest challenges developers face is handling paramsâ€”particularly when Next.js starts treating params as a Promise. This change comes with a warning when trying to access params directly in a component.\n\nIn this article, weâ€™ll explore why this warning occurs and how to resolve it by unwrapping the params Promise using React.use().\n\n### The Warning:\n\nWhen you access params directly in a Next.js component, you might encounter the following warning:\n\n```\nA param property was accessed directly with `params.username`. `params` is now a Promise and should be unwrapped with `React.use()` before accessing properties of the underlying params object. In this version of Next.js direct access to param properties is still supported to facilitate migration but in a future version you will be required to unwrap `params` with `React.use()`.\n\n```\n\nThe core issue here is that Next.js is transitioning to handle dynamic route parameters as asynchronous operations. params is no longer just a simple object that you can access synchronouslyâ€”it is now a Promise, which needs to be resolved before you can use it in your component.\n\n### Why is This Happening?\n\nNext.js aims to optimize handling dynamic routes by transitioning to a more asynchronous model. This means that dynamic parametersâ€”like params.usernameâ€”are treated as promises that need to be unwrapped before they can be accessed.\n\n### How to Fix It:\n\nTo fix the warning and ensure that your code remains future-proof, you need to unwrap the params Promise using React.use(). Hereâ€™s how to do it:\n\n### Steps to Resolve the Warning:\n\n1. Use React.use() to Unwrap the Promise: Since params is now a Promise, you need to resolve it asynchronously before accessing its properties.\n2. Handle Asynchronous Logic in useEffect: React's render cycle expects synchronous functions, so the asynchronous params should be handled outside the render process in a useEffect hook.\n\n### Code Example:\n\nHereâ€™s an updated version of the component that resolves the params Promise using React.use():\n\n```\n\"use client\";\n\nimport React, { useState, useEffect } from \"react\";\nimport axios from \"axios\";\n\nimport { Button } from \"@/components/ui/button\";\nimport { Textarea } from \"@",
